# Cline Rules for Self_AI Project
# These rules ensure careful, professional development practices

version: "1.0"

# =============================================================================
# CODEBASE AWARENESS
# =============================================================================

rules:

  - name: "read-before-modify"
    description: "Must read existing files before making changes"
    instruction: |
      Before editing ANY file, you MUST:
      1. Use the Read tool to load the file's full content
      2. Understand the existing patterns, conventions, and structure
      3. Identify what other files might be affected by your changes
      4. Never assume you know what a file contains - always read it first

  - name: "understand-dependencies"
    description: "Understand module dependencies before changing"
    instruction: |
      Before modifying a file, identify:
      1. What files import or depend on it (grep for imports)
      2. What tests exist for it
      3. What the caller/callee relationships are
      4. Check ARCHITECTURE.md for the module dependency tree

  - name: "python-import-order"
    description: "Maintain proper Python import organization"
    instruction: |
      Python imports MUST be in this order:
      1. Standard library imports (time, os, typing, etc.)
      2. Third-party imports (rlm, pytest, etc.)
      3. Local project imports (from rlm.core, etc.)
      Use 'strict' mode for zip() where lengths must match

  - name: "typescript-patterns"
    description: "Follow existing TypeScript/React patterns"
    instruction: |
      For TypeScript/React code:
      1. Use proper interface definitions for props and state
      2. Follow existing component patterns (functional components with hooks)
      3. Use Zustand for state management as established in the project
      4. Maintain Tailwind CSS class ordering conventions

# =============================================================================
# IMPACT ANALYSIS
# =============================================================================

  - name: "check-affected-files"
    description: "Analyze all files that could be affected by changes"
    instruction: |
      Before making changes, search for:
      1. All imports of the module you're modifying
      2. Type definitions that might need updating
      3. Test files that cover the code being changed
      4. Any related configuration files

  - name: "no-unnecessary-changes"
    description: "Don't make changes beyond what was requested"
    instruction: |
      1. Only change what's necessary to accomplish the task
      2. Don't refactor adjacent code or "improve" unrelated areas
      3. Don't add features that weren't explicitly requested
      4. Stay focused on the specific problem being solved

# =============================================================================
# TYPE SAFETY
# =============================================================================

  - name: "maintain-type-correctness"
    description: "Preserve and enforce type safety"
    instruction: |
      Python:
      1. Use explicit type hints for all function signatures
      2. Use Optional[T] instead of T | None for compatibility
      3. Use dataclasses for structured data (as done in base_agent.py)
      4. Check for protocol/interface patterns before modifying

      TypeScript:
      1. Run 'npm run type-check' after TypeScript changes
      2. Don't use 'any' type - use proper generics or unknown
      3. Keep interfaces aligned with backend Python types

  - name: "check-types-before-commit"
    description: "Verify type correctness before completing changes"
    instruction: |
      Run type checking commands:
      - Python: mypy on modified files if available
      - TypeScript: 'npm run type-check' in ui/ directory

# =============================================================================
# ERROR HANDLING
# =============================================================================

  - name: "preserve-error-handling"
    description: "Don't remove or weaken existing error handling"
    instruction: |
      1. Never remove try/except blocks unless replacing with better handling
      2. Maintain all error callbacks and their signatures
      3. Preserve BudgetExceededError, TimeoutExceededError, etc. handling
      4. Don't swallow exceptions without proper logging

  - name: "consistent-exception-types"
    description: "Use consistent exception hierarchy"
    instruction: |
      Use existing exception types from rlm/utils/exceptions.py:
      - BudgetExceededError
      - CancellationError
      - ErrorThresholdExceededError
      - TimeoutExceededError
      - TokenLimitExceededError
      Create new exceptions only when no existing type fits

# =============================================================================
# TESTING
# =============================================================================

  - name: "run-relevant-tests"
    description: "Run tests related to modified code"
    instruction: |
      After making changes:
      1. Identify relevant test files (tests/ directory)
      2. Run tests for the specific module modified
      3. Don't break existing test expectations
      4. If tests fail, fix the implementation, not the tests

  - name: "test-file-location"
    description: "Follow project test file conventions"
    instruction: |
      Test files are located at:
      - tests/ (root level)
      - rlm_source/tests/
      - Follow naming: test_<module_name>.py

# =============================================================================
# ARCHITECTURE ADHERENCE
# =============================================================================

  - name: "respect-module-boundaries"
    description: "Don't violate established module boundaries"
    instruction: |
      Follow the architecture in ARCHITECTURE.md:
      - rlm/core/ - RLM core functionality
      - rlm/agents/ - Agent management
      - rlm/environments/ - Execution environments
      - rlm/routing/ - Backend and environment routing
      - rlm/redux/ - State management slices
      - rlm/typechecking/ - Type checking system
      - ui/ - Next.js frontend

  - name: "understand-rlm-architecture"
    description: "Understand the RLM completion flow before modifying"
    instruction: |
      The RLM completion flow is:
      1. completion() -> _spawn_completion_context()
      2. _setup_prompt() -> message_history
      3. Loop: _completion_turn() -> environment.execute_code()
      4. _check_iteration_limits() -> final_answer or continue
      5. Changes to this flow need thorough review

# =============================================================================
# UI/FRONTEND SPECIFIC
# =============================================================================

  - name: "frontend-consistency"
    description: "Maintain frontend patterns and conventions"
    instruction: |
      UI directory (ui/):
      1. React 19 with functional components
      2. Zustand for state management (not Redux)
      3. Tailwind CSS for styling
      4. Run 'npm run lint' and 'npm run type-check' before finishing

  - name: "no-direct-state-mutation"
    description: "Use proper state management patterns"
    instruction: |
      1. Don't mutate Zustand stores directly - use setState patterns
      2. Follow existing slice patterns for redux/ state
      3. Maintain immutability in state updates

# =============================================================================
# DOCUMENTATION
# =============================================================================

  - name: "update-docstrings"
    description: "Update docstrings when changing function behavior"
    instruction: |
      1. If changing a function's behavior, update its docstring
      2. Document all parameters, return values, and exceptions
      3. Use the existing docstring style: Google-style or similar
      4. Update ARCHITECTURE.md if architectural decisions change

  - name: "no-undocumented-apis"
    description: "Don't expose undocumented interfaces"
    instruction: |
      1. All public methods should have docstrings
      2. Document callback signatures and their parameters
      3. Mark internal methods with underscore prefix

# =============================================================================
# REVIEW REQUIREMENTS
# =============================================================================

  - name: "verify-final-answer"
    description: "Ensure code is complete and correct before finishing"
    instruction: |
      Before completing a task:
      1. Read the modified files to verify changes are correct
      2. Run relevant tests
      3. Check that no import errors were introduced
      4. Verify type checking passes
      5. Confirm all affected files were considered

  - name: "break-glass-procedure"
    description: "Procedure for making significant architectural changes"
    instruction: |
      For significant changes:
      1. Explain what you're about to do
      2. Show the relevant existing code
      3. Explain your proposed change
      4. Wait for acknowledgment before proceeding
      5. This applies to: routing changes, agent lifecycle, state management

# =============================================================================
# WHAT NOT TO DO
# =============================================================================

prohibited:
  - name: "no-delete-without-check"
    description: "Never delete files or large code blocks without verification"
    instruction: "Always verify file contents with Read before deleting. Check git status to understand uncommitted changes."

  - name: "no-magic-numbers"
    description: "Don't use unexplained magic numbers"
    instruction: "Extract magic numbers into named constants. Example: MAX_RETRIES = 3 instead of hardcoded 3."

  - name: "no-force-push"
    description: "Never use --force with git push"
    instruction: "Force pushing can destroy colleagues' work. Always use regular push or create a new branch."

  - name: "no-random-files"
    description: "Don't create files in random locations"
    instruction: "Follow project structure. Test files go in tests/, docs in docs/, etc. Respect .kilo/ for kilo-specific files."

  - name: "no-skip-validation"
    description: "Don't skip linting or type checking"
    instruction: "Always run 'npm run lint' and 'npm run type-check' for UI changes. Address all warnings and errors."
